      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insight\n\nThe three pKa values of citric acid are relatively close together (2.90, 4.35, 5.65), reflecting the three carboxylate groups on the molecule — the hydroxyl group on the central carbon slightly modulates their acidity through inductive effects. The low pKa₁ (~2.90) makes citric acid a moderately strong organic acid, which is why it is so effective as a food acidulant and buffering agent in the pH range 2–6. The fully deprotonated citrate (L³⁻) is a powerful chelating agent for metal ions (as evidenced by the 19 metal systems in SRD-46 that include Ni²⁺, Cu²⁺, Fe³⁺, Al³⁺, and even NpO₂⁺), making it widely used in industrial metal cleaning, pharmaceuticals, and biochemistry.",
